        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/a/f4b2a3/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2024-03-02T21:13:56.053Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Essentially, yes.</p>\n<p>Ideally it would say ‚ÄúYou have unread notifications in ‚ÄòXYZ‚Äô‚Äù, XYZ being the name of the person or group chat that notification is coming from. if you have notifications set to ‚ÄúNo name or content‚Äù, then it should say ‚ÄúYou have unread notifications.‚Äù without the chat name.</p>\n<p>Also ideally, this has both a global option to set by default in notification settings (perhaps split into two options, one for 1:1 chats and one for group chats), and a per-chat option, similar to the global and per-chat options for disappearing messages.</p>\n<p><em>Also also ideally</em>, @ ing people sends out a notification as normal, so more pressing matters that require someone‚Äôs direct and immediate attention is exempt from this limitation in some way. There probably needs to be more planning in how that can be configured.</p>\n<p>In this hypothetical setup, the group chat with one‚Äôs friends can have lengthy discussions that you can visit at any time without endless notification noises, or if your attention is required <strong>now</strong>, they can ping you directly. Whereas the lesser used work group chat, where only reminders and bits of info are sent instead of lengthy conversations, send each message out as a notification.</p>",
